04647nam a22006495i 9780292795150DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212009txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927951507 a10.7560/7199582doi  a(DE-B1597)587620  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF3011.C57 -- F739 2009eb 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a307.762089924082211 aFreidenberg, Judith Noemí, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Invention of the Jewish Gaucho :bVilla Clara and the Construction of Argentine Identity /cJudith Noemí Freidenberg. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface: The Story behind the Story -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter One. Social Memory as Part of Villa Clara’s History -- tChapter Two. Entre Ríos, Mi País Immigrants Becoming Argentine in a Province -- tChapter Three. Colonia Clara and the Emergence of the “Jewish Gauchos” (1892–1902) -- tChapter Four From Jewish Gauchos to Gaucho Jews Regional Economic Development and Intercultural Relations at the End of the Nineteenth Century -- tChapter Five The Rise and Demise of Jewish Villa Clara (1902–1930s) -- tChapter Six Rural Depopulation and the Emergence of a Multiethnic and Socially Stratified Landscape in Villa Clara (1940s–1990s) -- tChapter Seven The Present as Politicized Past Legitimizing Social Structure through Heritage (1990s–2000s) -- tEpilogue: The Jewish Gaucho Revisited -- tAppendix I: Methodological Notes -- tAppendix II: Chronology of Relevant Events in Villa Clara -- tNotes -- tGlossary of Terms -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy the mid-twentieth century, Eastern European Jews had become one of Argentina's largest minorities. Some represented a wave of immigration begun two generations before; many settled in the province of Entre Ríos and founded an agricultural colony. Taking its title from the resulting hybrid of acculturation, The Invention of the Jewish Gaucho examines the lives of these settlers, who represented a merger between native cowboy identities and homeland memories. The arrival of these immigrants in what would be the village of Villa Clara coincided with the nation's new sense of liberated nationhood. In a meticulous rendition of Villa Clara's social history, Judith Freidenberg interweaves ethnographic and historical information to understand the saga of European immigrants drawn by Argentine open-door policies in the nineteenth century and its impact on the current transformation of immigration into multicultural discourses in the twenty-first century. Using Villa Clara as a case study, Freidenberg demonstrates the broad power of political processes in the construction of ethnic, class, and national identities. The Invention of the Jewish Gaucho draws on life histories, archives, material culture, and performances of heritage to enhance our understanding of a singular population—and to transform our approach to social memory itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aGauchoszArgentinazClaraxHistory. 0aJewszArgentinazClaraxHistory. 0aJewszArgentinazClaraxIdentity. 0aNational characteristics, ArgentinexHistory. 0aOral historyzArgentinazClara. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292795150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292795150/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK